00:22:07,359 --> 00:22:09,726
So are you liking it here so far?

259
00:22:10,495 --> 00:22:12,731
Uh, yeah, it's great.

260
00:22:12,732 --> 00:22:15,867
You know, if you need any help finding
an apartment, I know lots of places.

261
00:22:15,868 --> 00:22:18,335
I'm good. Thank you.

262
00:22:18,870 --> 00:22:20,804
Okay.

263
00:22:22,741 --> 00:22:24,810
HAZEL:
Stop flirting and get him in here.

264
00:22:24,811 --> 00:22:26,743
(LAUGHS) She...

265
00:22:28,680 --> 00:22:30,716
So I found three late
'80s Olds in the system.

266
00:22:30,717 --> 00:22:33,218
One's on cinder blocks, the
other two are accounted for.

267
00:22:33,219 --> 00:22:35,120
- So that means the one Jolene saw...
- Didn't come from here.

268
00:22:35,121 --> 00:22:36,887
Right.

269
00:22:37,956 --> 00:22:40,158
- Uh, this is Ben Wingate.
- Good morning.

270
00:22:40,159 --> 00:22:43,362
Good morning, Mr. Wingate.
And where did they find you?

271
00:22:43,363 --> 00:22:45,297
Toronto. 52 Division.

272
00:22:45,298 --> 00:22:47,966
You transferred from
Toronto to here?

273
00:22:47,967 --> 00:22:49,600
Yes, ma'am.

274
00:22:52,671 --> 00:22:54,805
Whose wife did you screw?

275
00:22:55,974 --> 00:22:58,210
Uh... (CHUCKLES)

276
00:22:58,211 --> 00:23:00,145
It... It was my choice.

277
00:23:00,146 --> 00:23:01,413
Why?

278
00:23:01,414 --> 00:23:03,181
I thought it was nice.

279
00:23:03,182 --> 00:23:05,851
- It's not nice.
- No, it's not nice at all.

280
00:23:05,852 --> 00:23:10,722
But it is interesting, isn't
it, that he shows up,

281
00:23:10,723 --> 00:23:14,524
when we have our first
murder in four years?

282
00:23:15,560 --> 00:23:16,928
(CHUCKLES)

283
00:23:16,929 --> 00:23:18,397
(CELL PHONE PLAYING MUSIC)

284
00:23:18,398 --> 00:23:19,698
Is that that?

285
00:23:19,699 --> 00:23:21,633
No, I didn't set that ring.

286
00:23:21,634 --> 00:23:23,068
- And how do you answer it?
- (CONTINUES RINGING)

287
00:23:23,069 --> 00:23:24,970
Just press that button.
There. Yeah.

288
00:23:24,971 --> 00:23:27,139
Stop. Shut up. How do you do that?

289
00:23:27,140 --> 00:23:28,306
- The bottom one.
- (RINGING STOPS)

290
00:23:28,307 --> 00:23:30,407
Oh, shit. I broke it.

291
00:23:30,575 --> 00:23:32,476
Give me that.

292
00:23:32,711 --> 00:23:34,945
I will fix this.

293
00:23:38,417 --> 00:23:40,550
Dismissed.

294
00:23:47,225 --> 00:23:50,095
BOB: My mother lived her
whole life in this town.

295
00:23:50,096 --> 00:23:54,699
She was one of the original
members of Civitan Zone 5.

296
00:23:54,700 --> 00:23:56,868
Every year, and I can remember,

297
00:23:56,869 --> 00:23:58,837
she would put on her best dress,

298
00:23:58,838 --> 00:24:02,306
go out and sell Claxton
cakes at Christmas.

299
00:24:03,675 --> 00:24:05,877
She once told me that if
I speak at her funeral,

300
00:24:05,878 --> 00:24:08,146
to make sure everyone
here remember her

301
00:24:08,147 --> 00:24:10,916
how she was before the sick.

302
00:24:10,917 --> 00:24:15,986
The Delia Chandler who had great
gams and could kick over her head.

303
00:24:16,822 --> 00:24:20,891
And who loved her family
and her community.

304
00:24:25,697 --> 00:24:27,798
(BELL TOLLING)

305
00:24:33,738 --> 00:24:35,774
- Oh, God, here she comes.
- Andrew.

306
00:24:35,775 --> 00:24:36,942
- Hey.
- Glynnis.

307
00:24:36,943 --> 00:24:38,443
Hey, Hazel.

308
00:24:38,444 --> 00:24:40,579
I know you call him Andy.

309
00:24:40,580 --> 00:24:43,215
I'm just trying to be respectful.

310
00:24:43,216 --> 00:24:45,016
Well, I call him Andrew.

311
00:24:45,017 --> 00:24:47,619
You can call him whatever
the hell you want,

312
00:24:47,620 --> 00:24:49,888
but if you want to be respectful,

313
00:24:49,889 --> 00:24:52,090
stop parking your car
outside our house.

314
00:24:52,091 --> 00:24:55,114
Excuse me, but some people have
jobs. My job happens to be...

315
00:24:55,115 --> 00:24:57,095
- to take care of this community.
- What is your job?

316
00:24:57,096 --> 00:24:59,431
- Because, at the bar...
- (CLAMORING)

317
00:24:59,432 --> 00:25:01,032
Why don't you go down the way?

318
00:25:01,033 --> 00:25:03,368
Why don't you go there for a while?

319
00:25:03,369 --> 00:25:06,304
HAZEL: I feel bad for Andy. I really,
I want him to be happy, I just...

320
00:25:06,305 --> 00:25:09,207
- Hey. We got a dead body out in Chamberlain.
- What does he see in her anyway?

321
00:25:09,208 --> 00:25:10,675
I mean, really. What did you say?

322
00:25:10,676 --> 00:25:14,145
Dead body out in Chamberlain.
Potential homicide.

323
00:25:14,146 --> 00:25:15,580
Well, that's not us.

324
00:25:15,581 --> 00:25:18,550
Well, Mason wants us to go
out there, so it is now.

325
00:25:18,551 --> 00:25:21,084
He called you and not me?

326
00:25:43,174 --> 00:25:44,743
- Body in there?
- Yeah.

327
00:25:44,744 --> 00:25:46,610
Victim's name?

328
00:25:47,245 --> 00:25:48,880
Michael Ullman.

329
00:25:48,881 --> 00:25:51,149
The horse trainer found
him this morning.

330
00:25:51,150 --> 00:25:52,651
She had the week off.

331
00:25:52,652 --> 00:25:56,454
Okay. I'd like to talk to her.

332
00:25:56,455 --> 00:26:00,492
Oh, I don't know where she is.
I told her that she could leave, I...

333
00:26:00,493 --> 00:26:03,361
All right, relax. Do you
know where she lives?

334
00:26:03,362 --> 00:26:05,730
Do you have her phone number?

335
00:26:05,731 --> 00:26:07,198
Okay, I'd like you to call her,

336
00:26:07,199 --> 00:26:09,534
ask her if she's seen
an old make Oldsmobile,

337
00:26:09,535 --> 00:26:13,003
gray, maybe between '85, '89.

338
00:26:14,573 --> 00:26:16,273
You can do that now.

339
00:26:16,875 --> 00:26:18,209
- Yeah.
- Good.

340
00:26:18,210 --> 00:26:19,910
Go.

341
00:26:28,053 --> 00:26:30,287
(HORSE NEIGHING)

342
00:27:07,859 --> 00:27:10,460
- Whoa.
- What is it?

343
00:27:12,998 --> 00:27:14,831
(SIGHS)

344
00:27:17,569 --> 00:27:19,504
No stomach.

345
00:27:19,505 --> 00:27:21,905
What do you mean
there's no stomach?

346
00:27:21,973 --> 00:27:23,940
It's been removed.

347
00:27:34,619 --> 00:27:36,853
(DOGS BARKING)

348
00:27:38,957 --> 00:27:40,692
RAY: Hazel?

349
00:27:40,693 --> 00:27:42,759
(DOGS WHIMPERING)

350
00:28:03,014 --> 00:28:05,315
RAY: What is it?

351
00:28:06,351 --> 00:28:09,085
I think I found his stomach.

352
00:28:22,333 --> 00:28:24,269
Two murders in three days,

353
00:28:24,270 --> 00:28:26,736
couple of 100 clicks apart.

354
00:28:27,272 --> 00:28:30,341
Something's in the air. Full moon?

355
00:28:30,342 --> 00:28:34,044
You think he's smart enough to
know our jurisdiction lines?

356
00:28:35,780 --> 00:28:37,849
You think this is
connected to Delia?

357
00:28:37,850 --> 00:28:39,851
Well, it's...

358
00:28:39,852 --> 00:28:43,655
A gruesome crime scene.
No forced entry.

359
00:28:43,656 --> 00:28:45,657
I don't think so.

360
00:28:45,658 --> 00:28:48,560
I mean, the victims
couldn't be more different.

361
00:28:48,561 --> 00:28:52,397
An old lady in town.
Rich guy on a farm.

362
00:28:52,398 --> 00:28:54,432
What's the connection?

363
00:28:54,433 --> 00:28:58,636
His face looked pretty
weird, didn't it? Hmm?

364
00:28:58,637 --> 00:29:02,907
It could have been manipulated
but it wasn't so obvious.

365
00:29:02,908 --> 00:29:05,542
Would it show up in the autopsy?

366
00:29:07,245 --> 00:29:10,013
Not if he was wearing
gloves. Thank you.

367
00:29:12,751 --> 00:29:14,551
You guys?

368
00:29:15,653 --> 00:29:17,654
All right.

369
00:29:43,047 --> 00:29:45,115
(EMILY HUMMING)

370
00:29:47,786 --> 00:29:52,457
Don't put your drink
on my photo album.

371
00:29:52,458 --> 00:29:56,359
You're gonna get a mark on it.

372
00:29:57,896 --> 00:29:59,597
Hmm.

373
00:29:59,598 --> 00:30:02,200
I haven't looked at
these in a long time.

374
00:30:02,201 --> 00:30:05,670
Oh, look at those false eyelashes.
Remember those?

375
00:30:05,671 --> 00:30:07,405
Yeah, they were ridiculous.

376
00:30:07,406 --> 00:30:10,175
Remember at your wedding
when you started laughing

377
00:30:10,176 --> 00:30:11,676
and you laughed so hard you cried

378
00:30:11,677 --> 00:30:14,512
and your eyelashes
slid down your cheek?

379
00:30:14,513 --> 00:30:17,182
I'm not the one that started
the laughing, you did.

380
00:30:17,183 --> 00:30:18,650
No, I didn't. I did... No.

381
00:30:18,651 --> 00:30:20,618
I was laughing because
you were laughing.

382
00:30:20,619 --> 00:30:25,023
You... Once you started
I had to join in.

383
00:30:25,024 --> 00:30:28,793
You have such an infectious laugh.

384
00:30:28,794 --> 00:30:31,963
You have a terrible memory.

385
00:30:31,964 --> 00:30:33,731
I don't have a terrible memory.

386
00:30:33,732 --> 00:30:36,166
That's exactly what happened.

387
00:30:37,702 --> 00:30:39,936
I miss that laugh.

388
00:30:47,579 --> 00:30:51,581
Okay. Well, enjoy your corpses.

389
00:30:59,924 --> 00:31:02,026
Thank you. I was just calling
to see if there'd been

390
00:31:02,027 --> 00:31:04,694
any recent murders in
your jurisdiction.

391
00:31:05,163 --> 00:31:07,263
Uh, sure, I can hold.

392
00:31:07,498 --> 00:31:09,100
Who is that?

393
00:31:09,101 --> 00:31:11,936
Hamilton Police Department.

394
00:31:11,937 --> 00:31:14,804
They're not sure they've
had any murders?

395
00:31:15,006 --> 00:31:17,340
Yeah, I'm still here.

396
00:31:22,080 --> 00:31:25,316
MASON: Got your requisition
for more manpower.

397
00:31:25,317 --> 00:31:27,252
Didn't I send somebody to you?

398
00:31:27,253 --> 00:31:30,421
Yes, but we still only have
two detectives, me and Ray.

399
00:31:30,422 --> 00:31:32,223
Well, that should be enough
to solve one murder.

400
00:31:32,224 --> 00:31:37,060
- Two. We think this is the work of a...
- Oh, good God.

401
00:31:37,262 --> 00:31:39,295
No, please. (CHUCKLES)

402
00:31:40,765 --> 00:31:42,100
Serial killer.

403
00:31:42,101 --> 00:31:43,534
Serial killer, huh?

404
00:31:43,535 --> 00:31:45,603
Do you know what we
call two murders here?

405
00:31:45,604 --> 00:31:47,372
The morning shift.

406
00:31:47,373 --> 00:31:49,406
You should do stand-up.

407
00:31:50,408 --> 00:31:52,477
Oh, wait a second. This is
your way of convincing me

408
00:31:52,478 --> 00:31:54,479
to give you the permanent
Commanding Officer job,

409
00:31:54,480 --> 00:31:57,482
with a suicide attempt
on your record.

410
00:31:57,483 --> 00:31:59,717
You lost your chance
when they had to pump

411
00:31:59,718 --> 00:32:02,819
painkillers out of
your belly in the ER.

412
00:32:06,324 --> 00:32:08,293
I'm telling you about two murders.

413
00:32:08,294 --> 00:32:10,328
Do you think I give a
shit what my title is?

414
00:32:10,329 --> 00:32:13,897
You would have been forced into retirement
without me, so watch your mouth.

415
00:32:16,434 --> 00:32:19,504
All right, Hazel, you want
my attention, you got it.

416
00:32:19,505 --> 00:32:21,371
What do you have?

417
00:32:22,840 --> 00:32:25,343
Look.

418
00:32:25,344 --> 00:32:29,314
You see how her mouth was
manipulated? We think his was too.

419
00:32:29,315 --> 00:32:31,482
And there was no forced
entry in either case,

420
00:32:31,483 --> 00:32:36,386
and Ullman's body was just a few
miles over the jurisdictional line.

421
00:32:36,421 --> 00:32:37,589
And?

422
00:32:37,590 --> 00:32:39,991
Well, so he's spreading his
targets far enough apart

423
00:32:39,992 --> 00:32:43,793
and he's changing the profile of the
victims so that we don't connect them.

424
00:32:44,529 --> 00:32:46,831
Serial killers leave calling cards.

425
00:32:46,832 --> 00:32:49,267
They want the world to
know what they're doing.

426
00:32:49,268 --> 00:32:52,603
I'm telling you, I know
that this is the same guy.

427
00:32:52,604 --> 00:32:54,405
You know nothing.

428
00:32:54,406 --> 00:32:57,308
You are guessing and you want me to
give you manpower to follow a hunch.

429
00:32:57,309 --> 00:33:01,145
All I need is one detective
with profiling experience.

430
00:33:01,146 --> 00:33:04,215
You know, if I knew that sending you to
Chamberlain was going to trigger this

431
00:33:04,216 --> 00:33:06,718
I would have sent somebody
who's better equipped.

432
00:33:06,719 --> 00:33:10,620
But, as I said, I don't
have anybody else.

433
00:33:15,626 --> 00:33:19,095
No. No specific age or gender.

434
00:33:20,031 --> 00:33:22,432
No it could look like anything.

435
00:33:24,669 --> 00:33:27,405
Yeah, uh, yeah, the mouth.

436
00:33:27,406 --> 00:33:29,640
That's exactly what
we're looking for.

437
00:33:29,641 --> 00:33:32,509
No, it could look like a suicide.

438
00:33:33,311 --> 00:33:36,513
Uh, could you send that over to me?

439
00:34:23,961 --> 00:34:25,962
Is she upstairs?

440
00:34:26,297 --> 00:34:27,532
She's sleeping.

441
00:34:27,533 --> 00:34:29,432
Oh.

442
00:34:29,700 --> 00:34:31,768
I just, um...

443
00:34:32,103 --> 00:34:35,171
I don't think now is a good time.

444
00:34:36,407 --> 00:34:38,174
Hmm.

445
00:34:38,176 --> 00:34:40,109
I'm sorry.

446
00:34:43,848 --> 00:34:45,848
I understand.

447
00:34:50,121 --> 00:34:52,121
Wait.

448
00:35:13,010 --> 00:35:15,379
Can you open your mouth for me?

449
00:35:15,380 --> 00:35:17,647
Stick out your tongue.

450
00:35:18,483 --> 00:35:20,051
Ah.

451
00:35:20,052 --> 00:35:22,854
What happens just
before you fall down?

452
00:35:22,855 --> 00:35:26,089
- It smells funny.
- Like what?

453
00:35:26,691 --> 00:35:28,758
Scrambled eggs.

454
00:35:30,027 --> 00:35:32,296
Do you like scrambled eggs?

455
00:35:32,297 --> 00:35:34,098
Not anymore.

456
00:35:34,099 --> 00:35:37,900
Hmm. I don't like
scrambled eggs either.

457
00:35:39,237 --> 00:35:40,371
What is it?

458
00:35:40,372 --> 00:35:43,673
This is mistletoe.

459
00:35:44,942 --> 00:35:47,210
It's like Christmas.

460
00:35:50,248 --> 00:35:53,249
- Oh, this is my favorite part.
- (LIQUID POURING)

461
00:35:59,957 --> 00:36:01,991
There.

462
00:36:06,164 --> 00:36:08,665
I'm not drinking that.

463
00:36:12,537 --> 00:36:14,837
(WHISPERING) Do you like honey?

464
00:36:14,972 --> 00:36:16,873
Yeah.

465
00:36:17,808 --> 00:36:20,343
Could you bring us some honey?

466
00:36:32,590 --> 00:36:35,126
I'm going to die, aren't I?

467
00:36:35,127 --> 00:36:40,364
Hmm. We're all going to die.
That's how God intended it.

468
00:36:40,365 --> 00:36:44,233
But how we live and how we die,

469
00:36:44,869 --> 00:36:47,303
that can be meaningful.

470
00:36:54,812 --> 00:36:57,280
Do you want to get better?

471
00:37:09,393 --> 00:37:11,761
I forgot to tell you.

472
00:37:12,129 --> 00:37:14,497
These cups are magic.

473
00:37:15,266 --> 00:37:17,068
If you sing to them,

474
00:37:17,069 --> 00:37:19,769
they'll make the tea taste better.

475
00:37:21,505 --> 00:37:24,006
(HUMMING)

476
00:37:29,547 --> 00:37:30,915
Your turn.

477
00:37:30,916 --> 00:37:32,782
(BOTH HUMMING)

478
00:37:37,622 --> 00:37:39,390
Keep singing.

479
00:37:39,391 --> 00:37:41,424
(HUMMING)

480
00:37:43,027 --> 00:37:45,194
Keep singing.

481
00:37:45,563 --> 00:37:47,730
(BOTH HUMMING)

482
00:37:48,299 --> 00:37:49,867
(TRAIN HORN BLOWING IN DISTANCE)

483
00:37:49,868 --> 00:37:51,868
(BOTH HUMMING)

484
00:37:57,575 --> 00:38:00,044
I looked into that
stuff you asked about.

485
00:38:00,045 --> 00:38:04,148
She had an e-mail account. Traded
gardening tips with a cousin in Calgary,

486
00:38:04,149 --> 00:38:07,184
and she visited a
soap opera chat room.

487
00:38:07,185 --> 00:38:09,185
She kept busy.

488
00:38:09,587 --> 00:38:11,856
That she did.

489
00:38:11,857 --> 00:38:14,892
The only thing she bought
was a gold cross necklace

490
00:38:14,893 --> 00:38:16,594
on overstock.com.

491
00:38:16,595 --> 00:38:19,397
I don't remember her
wearing necklaces.

492
00:38:19,398 --> 00:38:21,697
It's my wife's birthday next week.

493
00:38:22,867 --> 00:38:26,736
It's gonna be weird getting
something from her now.

494
00:38:30,508 --> 00:38:32,009
She never said it out loud,

495
00:38:32,010 --> 00:38:34,278
but she'd been suffering
for a long time.

496
00:38:34,279 --> 00:38:37,046
I could see she was ready
to go. It was in her eyes.

497
00:38:40,084 --> 00:38:41,918
Maybe he did her a favor.

498
00:38:42,653 --> 00:38:44,787
Doesn't make it right.

499
00:38:46,223 --> 00:38:48,191
I know.

500
00:38:48,459 --> 00:38:50,726
But it helps me sleep.

501
00:38:57,335 --> 00:38:59,468
(DOOR BELL RINGING)

502
00:38:59,670 --> 00:39:01,404
(MUSIC PLAYING)

503
00:39:01,405 --> 00:39:03,107
Wingate.

504
00:39:03,108 --> 00:39:04,608
You're gonna want to see this.

505
00:39:04,609 --> 00:39:06,010
Okay.

506
00:39:06,011 --> 00:39:07,511
Uh, maybe I should
walk you through that.

507
00:39:07,512 --> 00:39:09,447
No, that's fine. Good
night. Thank you.

508
00:39:09,448 --> 00:39:12,148
- Okay, are you sure?
- Do you like curry?

509
00:39:14,685 --> 00:39:16,552
Yeah.

510
00:39:17,254 --> 00:39:18,956
I love curry.

511
00:39:18,957 --> 00:39:22,425
Well, Hazel, let the kid in.

512
00:39:29,333 --> 00:39:32,470
Uh, I finally got all these
files I've been chasing down

513
00:39:32,471 --> 00:39:35,139
and I think we're missing
something with the faces.

514
00:39:35,140 --> 00:39:38,342
This is Gary Dewer, found by his
son, hanging from a chandelier.

515
00:39:38,343 --> 00:39:40,077
