00:41:17,175 --> 00:41:18,976
All right, stop it.

552
00:41:18,977 --> 00:41:21,278
What? Kids should talk
to their mothers.

553
00:41:21,279 --> 00:41:23,013
And some mothers talk too much.

554
00:41:23,014 --> 00:41:24,482
- Meaning me?
- Yes.

555
00:41:24,483 --> 00:41:26,183
- Okay.
- You're my mother. You're talking too much.

556
00:41:26,184 --> 00:41:28,252
- I'm hardly talking at all.
- Okay.

557
00:41:28,253 --> 00:41:29,620
- You're grilling him.
- I'm not!

558
00:41:29,621 --> 00:41:31,454
I'll clear.

559
00:41:37,795 --> 00:41:39,930
HAZEL: Next.

560
00:41:39,931 --> 00:41:43,033
RAY: Looks like he's singing.

561
00:41:43,034 --> 00:41:45,836
HAZEL: Next. What about this one?

562
00:41:45,837 --> 00:41:49,672
The mouth's pressed
together. What if...

563
00:41:50,574 --> 00:41:55,279
Seriously, what if
he's saying something?

564
00:41:55,280 --> 00:41:58,782
- He's not saying something, he's dead.
- I know.

565
00:41:58,783 --> 00:42:00,618
Well, is he saying anything?

566
00:42:00,619 --> 00:42:03,019
It's like a... Look, it's like a...

567
00:42:03,320 --> 00:42:05,122
Buh, like a buh.

568
00:42:05,123 --> 00:42:06,590
No, it's mmm...

569
00:42:06,591 --> 00:42:09,026
Mmm, mmm. Muh.

570
00:42:09,027 --> 00:42:10,961
Well, go to the next one.

571
00:42:10,962 --> 00:42:12,196
That's it, go on.

572
00:42:12,197 --> 00:42:13,697
BEN:
The upper lip is bent. It's buh.

573
00:42:13,698 --> 00:42:15,199
Now do it again.

574
00:42:15,200 --> 00:42:18,102
Say a sentence that has a "muh"
sound and a "buh" sound.

575
00:42:18,103 --> 00:42:19,370
You're going to see the difference.

576
00:42:19,371 --> 00:42:21,872
Your mother got hit by a bus.

577
00:42:21,873 --> 00:42:25,079
Yeah. Do you see...
Your... Mother...

578
00:42:25,105 --> 00:42:27,845
- Muh and buh, they're two entirely...
- Okay, try it again.

579
00:42:27,846 --> 00:42:30,195
BEN: Okay, that's a mouth
that's wide open, right?

580
00:42:30,196 --> 00:42:31,081
HAZEL: Go back.

581
00:42:31,082 --> 00:42:33,417
MATHIESEN: If you look at it,
the lips are curled in. Mmm.

582
00:42:33,418 --> 00:42:36,520
BEN: You're right if you're
talking about Portuguese.

583
00:42:36,521 --> 00:42:38,589
MATHIESEN:
I don't speak Portuguese.

584
00:42:38,590 --> 00:42:41,692
Or maybe it's not what they're
saying as individuals.

585
00:42:41,693 --> 00:42:46,063
Maybe they're syllables and
whoever manipulated their mouths

586
00:42:46,064 --> 00:42:50,433
is saying something with
them all... Will you be quiet!

587
00:42:53,237 --> 00:42:56,340
RAY: Well, some of them don't look
like they're saying anything together.

588
00:42:56,341 --> 00:42:58,008
Maybe it's in the
wrong order, then.

589
00:42:58,009 --> 00:42:59,677
Well, it's the order
that we found them.

590
00:42:59,678 --> 00:43:02,880
Well, maybe it's a different order. Maybe
it's the order in which they were killed.

591
00:43:02,881 --> 00:43:05,849
How about if we try it
going from west to east?

592
00:43:05,850 --> 00:43:09,620
So, that would be Dewar,
Grunwald, Fortnum. Try that.

593
00:43:09,621 --> 00:43:11,420
Okay.

594
00:43:15,459 --> 00:43:17,460
Faster.

595
00:43:18,529 --> 00:43:20,864
BEN: The vowels? Think
about how many vowels.

596
00:43:20,865 --> 00:43:23,300
Vowels make you open
your entire mouth.

597
00:43:23,301 --> 00:43:25,703
I mean, think about it.
It's only buh or muh,

598
00:43:25,704 --> 00:43:28,704
it's slow but it's
something like a...

599
00:43:29,506 --> 00:43:31,574
Jesus.

600
00:43:52,396 --> 00:43:54,932
MATHIESEN: Lie-bee-la.

601
00:43:54,933 --> 00:43:57,534
Lie-bee-la. Lie-bee-la?

602
00:43:57,535 --> 00:44:01,505
No, no, no, it's Lie-bee-ra.

603
00:44:01,506 --> 00:44:03,307
It's an "R". Look at, uh...

604
00:44:03,308 --> 00:44:05,209
Look at his mouth.

605
00:44:05,210 --> 00:44:07,277
That's an L. Now can you flip
to Ruby Marshall, please?

606
00:44:07,278 --> 00:44:10,848
Yeah. See how the tongue is kind
of on the side of the mouth?

607
00:44:10,849 --> 00:44:13,917
That's an R. It's ra.

608
00:44:13,918 --> 00:44:18,320
As in, "You're wrong."

609
00:44:18,956 --> 00:44:21,790
Lie-bee-ra

610
00:44:21,859 --> 00:44:24,660
ri-e. Ra-ri-e.

611
00:44:25,562 --> 00:44:30,199
It's Professor Plume in the
lie-bee-ra-ri-e with the candlestick.

612
00:44:32,036 --> 00:44:34,370
(SIGHS) I'm done.

613
00:45:17,881 --> 00:45:23,187
Hey, guys. What if
it isn't English?

614
00:45:23,188 --> 00:45:25,654
What do you mean, like French?

615
00:45:27,124 --> 00:45:29,191
Huh.

616
00:45:35,999 --> 00:45:40,804
(GASPS) They were all Catholic.

617
00:45:40,805 --> 00:45:45,375
It's Latin. I guarantee
you, this is Latin.

618
00:45:45,376 --> 00:45:48,045
Latin? Who speaks Latin?

619
00:45:48,046 --> 00:45:49,880
People in Latin America.

620
00:45:49,881 --> 00:45:53,650
Oh, God. It... Listen,
it sounds like Latin.

621
00:45:53,651 --> 00:45:55,285
- It's not that.
- Lie-bee-ra.

622
00:45:55,286 --> 00:45:57,553
BEN: I guarantee you that's Latin.

623
00:46:04,795 --> 00:46:09,465
Well, I know the words, but I don't
actually speak the language.

624
00:46:09,466 --> 00:46:11,168
Oh.

625
00:46:11,169 --> 00:46:15,606
Now, Father Price at Saint Xavier,
he was a linguistics professor.

626
00:46:15,607 --> 00:46:17,606
He could help.

627
00:46:54,745 --> 00:46:57,981
When you get to be my age
it's a comfort to have

628
00:46:57,982 --> 00:47:01,752
those reminders of
some accomplishments.

629
00:47:01,753 --> 00:47:04,620
- Sit, sit down, please.
- Thank you, Father.

630
00:47:04,988 --> 00:47:06,957
They're your students?

631
00:47:06,958 --> 00:47:08,625
No.

632
00:47:08,626 --> 00:47:12,261
We used to take in orphans
and find them homes.

633
00:47:12,529 --> 00:47:15,097
But you don't anymore.

634
00:47:15,132 --> 00:47:17,166
No.

635
00:47:18,302 --> 00:47:21,305
But you didn't come here
to talk about that.

636
00:47:21,306 --> 00:47:23,407
No.

637
00:47:23,408 --> 00:47:27,910
Could you help me and
tell me what that means?

638
00:47:28,645 --> 00:47:32,683
(CHUCKLES) <i>Libera.</i>

639
00:47:32,684 --> 00:47:35,485
It's the imperative
of the Latin verb

640
00:47:35,486 --> 00:47:39,890
that is at the root
of liberty. Liberate.

641
00:47:39,891 --> 00:47:44,026
Well, let me see.
With the E following,

642
00:47:44,361 --> 00:47:47,631
<i>eos. Libera eos.</i>

643
00:47:47,632 --> 00:47:49,299
Deliver them.

644
00:47:49,300 --> 00:47:55,205
So does that phrase mean
anything special to you?

645
00:47:55,206 --> 00:47:58,175
<i>Libera nos domine.</i>

646
00:47:58,176 --> 00:48:01,178
Now, that's quite a common phrase.

647
00:48:01,179 --> 00:48:06,014
Free us Lord. Um, <i>Libera.</i>

648
00:48:06,450 --> 00:48:11,555
<i>Re-Eos. Libera-re-Eos.
Libera-re-Eos.</i>

649
00:48:11,556 --> 00:48:14,458
- And what does that mean?
- Set them free.

650
00:48:14,459 --> 00:48:17,027
So, they're similar.

651
00:48:17,028 --> 00:48:19,396
Similar, yes, but not at
all the same. Do you...

652
00:48:19,397 --> 00:48:22,299
Do you know anything about the
history of the written Bible?

653
00:48:22,300 --> 00:48:25,736
Well, I always thought
it was kind of like

654
00:48:25,737 --> 00:48:29,805
- a 2,000 year-old game of broken telephone.
- (CHUCKLES)

655
00:48:31,041 --> 00:48:35,612
Let me explain. The
Bible, as we know it,

656
00:48:35,613 --> 00:48:39,883
was composed around
400 <i>Anno Domini.</i>

657
00:48:39,884 --> 00:48:42,653
It contained an oral component,

658
00:48:42,654 --> 00:48:46,924
because elements of that Bible were
prohibited from being written down.

659
00:48:46,925 --> 00:48:49,426
Forbidden songs.
Blessings conferred

660
00:48:49,427 --> 00:48:52,362
upon the closest of
Christ's disciples.

661
00:48:52,363 --> 00:48:56,667
These were meant to be communicated
only between high priests,

662
00:48:56,668 --> 00:48:59,703
because once the
blessing was offered,

663
00:48:59,704 --> 00:49:02,406
the listener became
the keeper of it.

664
00:49:02,407 --> 00:49:06,176
And the speaker, on
certain occasions,

665
00:49:06,177 --> 00:49:09,413
offered himself up as a sacrifice.

666
00:49:09,414 --> 00:49:11,815
For what?

667
00:49:11,816 --> 00:49:18,153
<i>Liberare Eos.</i> A sacrifice
to set them free.

668
00:49:18,855 --> 00:49:22,157
- So you do know what it means.
- (CHUCKLES)

669
00:49:22,225 --> 00:49:24,693
Uh, I have...

670
00:49:25,162 --> 00:49:28,265
Oh, here.

671
00:49:28,266 --> 00:49:33,236
When the women went to complete
the burial rites at Christ's tomb,

672
00:49:33,237 --> 00:49:34,905
- they found it empty.
- Hmm.

673
00:49:34,906 --> 00:49:38,642
Their service was rewarded by the
Holy Ghost with that prayer.

674
00:49:38,643 --> 00:49:41,276
A consecration against death.

675
00:49:41,478 --> 00:49:43,146
So immortality?

676
00:49:43,147 --> 00:49:45,349
No, not quite.

677
00:49:45,350 --> 00:49:49,785
<i>Liberare Eos</i> is a
prayer of resurrection.

678
00:49:52,422 --> 00:49:54,923
Okay.

679
00:49:56,059 --> 00:49:59,228
Ah, back then, people
had deeper faith.

680
00:49:59,229 --> 00:50:01,463
Blind faith.

681
00:50:01,598 --> 00:50:04,099
Profound faith.

682
00:50:07,671 --> 00:50:11,375
Well, how exactly does it work?

683
00:50:11,376 --> 00:50:13,942
I promise I won't tell anybody.

684
00:50:15,479 --> 00:50:19,783
It required 12 willing souls

685
00:50:19,784 --> 00:50:24,187
to sacrifice themselves
to bring back the one.

686
00:50:24,188 --> 00:50:27,424
Now, the operative
word is, "willing."

687
00:50:27,425 --> 00:50:30,359
Once the final life was given,

688
00:50:31,194 --> 00:50:35,832
the prayer was spoken
aloud and witnessed.

689
00:50:35,833 --> 00:50:41,271
And then those 12 disciples
who sacrificed themselves

690
00:50:41,272 --> 00:50:44,107
were granted eternal salvation.

691
00:50:44,108 --> 00:50:48,678
And the chosen one was reborn.

692
00:50:48,679 --> 00:50:52,682
I mean, you know, this is
early Christian mysticism.

693
00:50:52,683 --> 00:50:55,619
This pre-dates even the Vatican.

694
00:50:55,620 --> 00:50:58,153
And do you really
believe this stuff?

695
00:50:58,789 --> 00:51:03,427
(SIGHS) I did, yes, once.

696
00:51:03,428 --> 00:51:05,796
But times are different now.

697
00:51:05,797 --> 00:51:08,999
Unwavering belief in the church is

698
00:51:09,000 --> 00:51:12,235
difficult to sustain.

699
00:51:12,236 --> 00:51:15,971
Perhaps, I mean,
I think quite possibly,

700
00:51:16,173 --> 00:51:18,540
with good reason.

701
00:51:19,342 --> 00:51:23,747
I find it fascinating
that someone like you

702
00:51:23,748 --> 00:51:28,285
would be interested in
unearthing this prayer

703
00:51:28,286 --> 00:51:32,589
that has been for 1,500 years,

704
00:51:32,590 --> 00:51:35,624
by and large, lost.

705
00:51:36,526 --> 00:51:39,528
I think somebody may have found it.

706
00:52:26,676 --> 00:52:29,980
If you can sleep on the floor
why can't I sleep in my chair?

707
00:52:29,981 --> 00:52:32,314
'Cause I'm special.

708
00:52:33,049 --> 00:52:35,951
- Let's go up.
- You certainly are.

709
00:52:48,365 --> 00:52:51,535
Hey! Do you remember that gold cross
that Delia Chandler bought online?

710
00:52:51,536 --> 00:52:53,803
- Yeah.
- They never got it.

711
00:52:53,804 --> 00:52:55,784
Nothing showed up
at Delia's either.

712
00:52:56,306 --> 00:52:58,441
- So?
- Overstock.com shipped through

713
00:52:58,442 --> 00:53:02,679
a PO box in Port Hardy, BC,
addressed to Jane Buck.

714
00:53:02,680 --> 00:53:04,789
- BC?
- I called Delia's son.

715
00:53:04,815 --> 00:53:06,983
He's never heard of her.

716
00:53:06,984 --> 00:53:09,519
The post office wouldn't give out
any information over the phone,

717
00:53:09,520 --> 00:53:11,922
so I looked up Jane Buck in the
local white pages and guess what?

718
00:53:11,923 --> 00:53:13,323
What?

719
00:53:13,324 --> 00:53:18,693
There's a phone number and home
address 10 miles from that PO box.

720
00:53:31,241 --> 00:53:33,310
- Go for it.
- (LINE RINGING)

721
00:53:33,311 --> 00:53:35,310
Oh.

722
00:53:42,385 --> 00:53:44,554
- WOMAN: (OVER SPEAKER) <i>Hello?</i>
- Hello.

723
00:53:44,555 --> 00:53:46,755
Is this Jane Buck?

724
00:53:47,057 --> 00:53:49,159
<i>Who is this?</i>

725
00:53:49,160 --> 00:53:51,628
This is Officer Ben Wingate, from
the Fort Dundas Police Department.

726
00:53:51,629 --> 00:53:56,331
You wouldn't happen to know anyone by
the name of Delia Chandler, would you?

727
00:53:59,069 --> 00:54:00,837
<i>This isn't a good time.</i>

728
00:54:00,838 --> 00:54:04,506
Okay. When would be a good time?

729
00:54:09,446 --> 00:54:10,880
Could be a lead.

730
00:54:10,881 --> 00:54:13,783
Come on, you gotta let me go.

731
00:54:13,784 --> 00:54:17,587
I would love to let you go, but I don't
have the money to fly you there.

732
00:54:17,588 --> 00:54:22,659
My mom gives me Air Miles every year
for Christmas. I've never used them.

733
00:54:22,660 --> 00:54:23,927
(DOOR OPENING)

734
00:54:23,928 --> 00:54:26,161
I found our Olds.

735
00:54:36,506 --> 00:54:39,441
This is where he got the ticket.

736
00:54:41,578 --> 00:54:46,181
Okay. Well, let's start
knocking on some doors.

737
00:54:50,453 --> 00:54:52,389
So you just let him in?

738
00:54:52,390 --> 00:54:56,092
I spoke with him for quite
a while at the diner.

739
00:54:56,093 --> 00:55:00,363
My daughter was very sick and I
believed that he could help her.

740
00:55:00,364 --> 00:55:03,700
I was desperate. Nothing
else was working.

741
00:55:03,701 --> 00:55:05,835
RAY: What did he look like?

742
00:55:05,836 --> 00:55:08,438
Tall, thin.

743
00:55:08,439 --> 00:55:10,407
He had a big bag.

744
00:55:10,408 --> 00:55:15,612
Dark coat. Sandy
blonde hair. Beard.

745
00:55:15,613 --> 00:55:20,250
I remember he had kind eyes.
I don't know if that helps.

746
00:55:20,251 --> 00:55:23,320
Okay, so you let him in
and then what happened?

747
00:55:23,321 --> 00:55:25,455
He gave her some tea.

748
00:55:25,456 --> 00:55:29,959
He came out, he said
she was sleeping.

749
00:55:29,960 --> 00:55:34,996
So I looked in on her. She looked
peaceful, so I let her rest.

750
00:55:35,899 --> 00:55:41,036
Then she woke up screaming,
vomiting, burning up.

751
00:55:41,438 --> 00:55:43,540
I took her to the hospital.

752
00:55:43,541 --> 00:55:47,742
They told us it was a 50-50 chance
she'd make it through the night.

753
00:55:49,145 --> 00:55:54,616
Two days later the vomiting
stopped and the MRI was clear.

754
00:55:57,253 --> 00:55:58,655
Yeah, hon.

755
00:55:58,656 --> 00:56:00,256
(WHISPERING)
I want to show you a drawing.

756
00:56:00,257 --> 00:56:03,458
Okay. Excuse me just for a second.

757
00:56:06,363 --> 00:56:09,132
Killers kill. They don't heal.

758
00:56:09,133 --> 00:56:13,303
You know, Jesus raised a
little girl from the dead.

759
00:56:13,304 --> 00:56:16,239
She was about that age. It was one
of his top 10 miracles, actually.

760
00:56:16,240 --> 00:56:17,674
You're referencing scriptures now?

